The pur- port clearly is that no perpetually binding close can be given to a civil war by an agreement limiting the prince's prerogatives, in accordance with what Ayala has taught in the preceding chapter about its not being a duty to keep faith with rebels.

The eighth is a commonplace chapter on lawful stratagem and fraud in war, in which no principles are laid down by Which cases may be distinguished.

The ninth chapter is on the rights of ambassadors‚ and contains nothing remarkable except Ayala's refusal of such rights to rebels and to subjects who serve an enemy with treasonable intent.
